[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] A data parallel job on an array of *n* elements can be divided equally among all the processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Let us assume we want to sum all the elements of the given array and the time for a single addition operation is Ta time units.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In the case of sequential execution, the time taken by the process will be *n*×Ta time units as it sums up all the elements of an array.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] On the other hand, if we execute this job as a data parallel job on 4 processors the time taken would reduce to (*n*/4)×Ta + merging overhead time units.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Parallel execution results in a speedup of 4 over sequential execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The locality of data references plays an important part in evaluating the performance of a data parallel programming model.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Locality of data depends on the memory accesses performed by the program as well as the size of the cache.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Exploitation of the concept of data parallelism started in 1960s with the development of the Solomon machine.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The Solomon machine, also called a vector processor, was developed to expedite the performance of mathematical operations by working on a large data array (operating on multiple data in consecutive time steps).
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Concurrency of data operations was also exploited by operating on multiple data at the same time using a single instruction.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] These processors were called 'array processors'.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In the 1980s, the term was introduced to describe this programming style, which was widely used to program Connection Machines in data parallel languages like C*.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Today, data parallelism is best exemplified in graphics processing units (GPUs), which use both the techniques of operating on multiple data in space and time using a single instruction.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Most data parallel hardware supports only a fixed number of parallel levels, often only one.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] This means that within a parallel operation it is not possible to launch more parallel operations recursively, and means that programmers cannot make use of nested hardware parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The programming language NESL was an early effort at implementing a nested data-parallel programming model on flat parallel machines, and in particular introduced the flattening transformation that transforms nested data parallelism to flat data parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] This work was continued by other languages such as Data Parallel Haskell and Futhark, although arbitrary nested data parallelism is not widely available in current data-parallel programming languages.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different distributed data.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In some situations, a single execution thread controls operations on all the data.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In others, different threads control the operation, but they execute the same code.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] For instance, consider matrix multiplication and addition in a sequential manner as discussed in the example.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Below is the sequential pseudo-code for multiplication and addition of two matrices where the result is stored in the matrix *C*.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The pseudo-code for multiplication calculates the dot product of two matrices *A*, *B* and stores the result into the output matrix *C*.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] If the following programs were executed sequentially, the time taken to calculate the result would be of the $O(n^{3})$ (assuming row lengths and column lengths of both matrices are n) and $O(n)$ for multiplication and addition respectively.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] We can exploit data parallelism in the preceding code to execute it faster as the arithmetic is loop independent.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Parallelization of the matrix multiplication code is achieved by using OpenMP.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] An OpenMP directive, "omp parallel for" instructs the compiler to execute the code in the for loop in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] For multiplication, we can divide matrix A and B into blocks along rows and columns respectively.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] This allows us to calculate every element in matrix C individually thereby making the task parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] For example: *A[m x n] dot B [n x k]* can be finished in $O(n)$ instead of $O(m*n*k)$ when executed in parallel using *m*k* processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] It can be observed from the example that a lot of processors will be required as the matrix sizes keep on increasing.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Keeping the execution time low is the priority but as the matrix size increases, we are faced with other constraints like complexity of such a system and its associated costs.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Therefore, constraining the number of processors in the system, we can still apply the same principle and divide the data into bigger chunks to calculate the product of two matrices.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] For addition of arrays in a data parallel implementation, let's assume a more modest system with two central processing units (CPU) A and B, CPU A could add all elements from the top half of the arrays, while CPU B could add all elements from the bottom half of the arrays.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Since the two processors work in parallel, the job of performing array addition would take one half the time of performing the same operation in serial using one CPU alone.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] In an SPMD system executed on 2 processor system, both CPUs will execute the code.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Data parallelism emphasizes the distributed (parallel) nature of the data, as opposed to the processing (task parallelism).
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Most real programs fall somewhere on a continuum between task parallelism and data parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into four discrete steps.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Data and task parallelism, can be simultaneously implemented by combining them together for the same application.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] This is called Mixed data and task parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Mixed parallelism requires sophisticated scheduling algorithms and software support.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] It is the best kind of parallelism when communication is slow and number of processors is large.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Mixed data and task parallelism has many applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] The data is divided among different sub-circuits and parallelism is achieved with orchestration from the tasks.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] OpenMP: It's an Application Programming Interface (API) which supports shared memory programming models on multiple platforms of multiprocessor systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Since version 4.5, OpenMP is also able to target devices other than typical CPUs.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] It can program FPGAs, DSPs, GPUs and more.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] It is not confined to GPUs like OpenACC.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] CUDA and OpenACC: CUDA and OpenACC (respectively) are parallel computing API platforms designed to allow a software engineer to utilize GPUs' computational units for general purpose processing.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Threading Building Blocks and RaftLib: Both open source programming environments that enable mixed data/task parallelism in C/C++ environments across heterogeneous resources.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Data parallelism finds its applications in a variety of fields ranging from physics, chemistry, biology, material sciences to signal processing.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Sciences imply data parallelism for simulating models like molecular dynamics, sequence analysis of genome data and other physical phenomenon.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Driving forces in signal processing for data parallelism are video encoding, image and graphics processing, wireless communications to name a few.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Data-intensive computing is a class of parallel computing applications which use a data parallel approach to process large volumes of data typically terabytes or petabytes in size and typically referred to as big data.
[src:rayon-parallel/data-parallelism] Computing applications that devote most of their execution time to computational requirements are deemed compute-intensive, whereas applications are deemed data-intensive if they require large volumes of data and devote most of their processing time to input/output and manipulation of data.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Rayon is a data-parallelism library that makes it easy to convert sequential computations into parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] It is lightweight and convenient for introducing parallelism into existing code.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] It guarantees data-race free executions and takes advantage of parallelism when sensible, based on work-load at runtime.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] First, you will need to add `rayon` to your `Cargo.toml`.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Next, to use parallel iterators or the other high-level methods, you need to import several traits.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Those traits are bundled into the module `rayon::prelude`.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] It is recommended that you import all of these traits at once by adding `use rayon::prelude::*` at the top of each module that uses Rayon methods.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] These traits give you access to the `par_iter` method which provides parallel implementations of many iterative functions such as `map`, `for_each`, `filter`, `fold`, and more.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Rayon extends many of the types found in the standard library with parallel iterator implementations.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] The modules in the `rayon` crate mirror `std` itself: so, e.g., the `option` module in Rayon contains parallel iterators for the `Option` type, which is found in the `option` module of `std`.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Similarly, the `collections` module in Rayon offers parallel iterator types for the `collections` from `std`.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] You will rarely need to access these submodules unless you need to name iterator types explicitly.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] Rayon has limited support for targets without `std` threading implementations.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] See the `rayon_core` documentation for more information about its global fallback.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] and have easy access to the various traits and methods you will need.
[src:rayon-parallel/latest-rayon] You will rarely need to interact with it directly unless you have need to name one of the iterator types.
