[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] For simple loops, where each iteration is independent of the others, loop-level parallelism can be embarrassingly parallel, as parallelizing only requires assigning a process to handle each iteration.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] However, many algorithms are designed to run sequentially, and fail when parallel processes race due to dependence within the code.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Sequential algorithms are sometimes applicable to parallel contexts with slight modification.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Usually, though, they require process synchronization.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Synchronization can be either implicit, via message passing, or explicit, via synchronization primitives like semaphores.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following code operating on a list `l`, where `l.size() == n`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration of the loop takes the value from the current index of `l`, and increments it by 10.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] If statement `s1` takes `T` time to execute, then the loop takes time `n * T` to execute sequentially, ignoring time taken by loop constructs.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Now, consider a system with `p` processors where `p > n`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] If `n` threads run in parallel, the time to execute all `n` steps is reduced to `T`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Less simple cases produce inconsistent, i.e. non-serializable outcomes.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following loop operating on the same list `l`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration sets the current index to be the value of the previous plus ten.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] When run sequentially, each iteration is guaranteed that the previous iteration will already have the correct value.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] With multiple threads, process scheduling and other considerations prevent the execution order from guaranteeing an iteration will execute only after its dependence is met.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] It very well may happen before, leading to unexpected results.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Serializability can be restored by adding synchronization to preserve the dependence on previous iterations.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] There are several types of dependences that can be found within code.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] In order to preserve the sequential behaviour of a loop when run in parallel, True Dependence must be preserved.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Anti-Dependence and Output Dependence can be dealt with by giving each process its own copy of variables (known as privatization).
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->T s3`, meaning that s2 has a true dependence on s3 because s2 writes to the variable `a`, which s3 reads from.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->A s3`, meaning that s2 has an anti-dependence on s3 because s2 reads from the variable `b` before s3 writes to it.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->O s3`, meaning that s2 has an output dependence on s3 because both write to the variable `a`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->I s3`, meaning that s2 has an input dependence on s3 because s2 and s3 both read from variable `c`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] In loop-independent dependence, loops have inter-iteration dependence, but do not have dependence between iterations.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration may be treated as a block and performed in parallel without other synchronization efforts.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] In the following example code used for swapping the values of two array of length n, there is a loop-independent dependence of `s1 ->T s3`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] In loop-carried dependence, statements in an iteration of a loop depend on statements in another iteration of the loop.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Loop-Carried Dependence uses a modified version of the dependence notation seen earlier.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Example of loop-carried dependence where `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`, where `i` indicates the current iteration, and `i + 1` indicates the next iteration.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] A Loop-carried dependence graph graphically shows the loop-carried dependencies between iterations.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration is listed as a node on the graph, and directed edges show the true, anti, and output dependencies between each iteration.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] There are a variety of methodologies for parallelizing loops.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each implementation varies slightly in how threads synchronize, if at all.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] In addition, parallel tasks must somehow be mapped to a process.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] These tasks can either be allocated statically or dynamically.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Research has shown that load-balancing can be better achieved through some dynamic allocation algorithms than when done statically.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into the following discrete steps.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Each concrete loop-parallelization below implicitly performs them.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] When a loop has a loop-carried dependence, one way to parallelize it is to distribute the loop into several different loops.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Statements that are not dependent on each other are separated so that these distributed loops can be executed in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] For example, consider the following code.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The loop has a loop carried dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]` but s2 and s1 do not have a loop-independent dependence so we can rewrite the code as follows.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Note that now loop1 and loop2 can be executed in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Instead of single instruction being performed in parallel on different data as in data level parallelism, here different loops perform different tasks on different data.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] We call this type of parallelism either function or task parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] DOALL parallelism exists when statements within a loop can be executed independently (situations where there is no loop-carried dependence).
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] For example, the following code does not read from the array `a`, and does not update the arrays `b, c`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] No iterations have a dependence on any other iteration.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The following example, using a simplified pseudo code, shows how a loop might be parallelized to execute each iteration independently.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] DOACROSS Parallelism exists where iterations of a loop are parallelized by extracting calculations that can be performed independently and running them simultaneously.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Synchronization exists to enforce loop-carried dependence.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following, synchronous loop with dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The first line, `int tmp = b[i] + 1;`, has no loop-carried dependence.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The loop can then be parallelized by computing the temp value in parallel, and then synchronizing the assignment to `a[i]`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] DOPIPE Parallelism implements pipelined parallelism for loop-carried dependence where a loop iteration is distributed over multiple, synchronized loops.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] The goal of DOPIPE is to act like an assembly line, where one stage is started as soon as there is sufficient data available for it from the previous stage.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following, synchronous code with dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] s1 must be executed sequentially, but s2 has no loop-carried dependence. s2 could be executed in parallel using DOALL Parallelism after performing all calculations needed by s1 in series.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] However, the speedup is limited if this is done.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] A better approach is to parallelize such that the s2 corresponding to each s1 executes when said s1 is finished.
[src:rayon-parallel/loop-level-parallelism] Implementing pipelined parallelism results in the following set of loops, where the second loop may execute for an index as soon as the first loop has finished its corresponding index.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] A **multi-core processor** (**MCP**) is a microprocessor on a single integrated circuit (IC) with two or more separate central processing units (CPUs), called *cores* to emphasize their multiplicity (for example, *dual-core* or *quad-core*).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Each core reads and executes program instructions, specifically ordinary CPU instructions (such as add, move data, and branch).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] However, the MCP can run instructions on separate cores at the same time, increasing overall speed for programs that support multithreading or other parallel computing techniques.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Manufacturers typically integrate the cores onto a single IC die, known as a **chip multiprocessor** (**CMP**), or onto multiple dies in a single chip package.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] As of 2024, the microprocessors used in almost all new personal computers are multi-core.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] A multi-core processor implements multiprocessing in a single physical package.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Designers may couple cores in a multi-core device tightly or loosely.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] For example, cores may or may not share caches, and they may implement message passing or shared-memory inter-core communication methods.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Common network topologies used to interconnect cores include bus, ring, two-dimensional mesh, and crossbar.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Just as with single-processor systems, cores in multi-core systems may implement architectures such as VLIW, superscalar, vector, or multithreading.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Multi-core processors are widely used across many application domains, including general-purpose, embedded, network, digital signal processing (DSP), and graphics (GPU).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Core count goes up to even dozens, and for specialized chips over 10,000, and in supercomputers (i.e. clusters of chips) the count can go over 10 million (and in one case up to 20 million processing elements total in addition to host processors).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The improvement in performance gained by the use of a multi-core processor depends very much on the software algorithms used and their implementation.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In particular, possible gains are limited by the fraction of the software that can run in parallel simultaneously on multiple cores; this effect is described by Amdahl's law.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the best case, so-called embarrassingly parallel problems may realize speedup factors near the number of cores, or even more if the problem is split up enough to fit within each core's cache(s), avoiding use of much slower main-system memory.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Most applications, however, are not accelerated as much unless programmers invest effort in refactoring.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The parallelization of software is a significant ongoing topic of research.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Cointegration of multiprocessor applications provides flexibility in network architecture design.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Adaptability within parallel models is an additional feature of systems utilizing these protocols.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the consumer market, dual-core processors (that is, microprocessors with two units) started becoming commonplace on personal computers in the late 2000s.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the early 2010s, quad-core processors were also being adopted in that era for higher-end systems before becoming standard by the mid 2010s.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the late 2010s, hexa-core (six cores) started entering the mainstream and since the early 2020s has overtaken quad-core in many spaces.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The terms *multi-core* and *dual-core* most commonly refer to central processing units (CPUs), but are sometimes applied to digital signal processors (DSPs) and systems on chip (SoCs).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The terms are generally used only to refer to multi-core microprocessors that are manufactured on the *same* integrated circuit die; separate microprocessor dies in the same package are generally referred to by another name, such as *multi-chip module*.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This article uses the terms "multi-core" and "dual-core" for CPUs manufactured on the *same* integrated circuit, unless otherwise noted.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In contrast to multi-core systems, the term *multi-CPU* refers to multiple physically separate processing-units (which often contain special circuitry to facilitate communication between each other).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The terms *many-core* and *massively multi-core* are sometimes used to describe multi-core architectures with an especially high number of cores (tens to thousands).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Some systems use many soft microprocessor cores placed on a single FPGA.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Each "core" can be considered a "semiconductor intellectual property core" as well as a CPU core.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] While manufacturing technology improves, reducing the size of individual gates, physical limits of semiconductor-based microelectronics have become a major design concern.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] These physical limitations can cause significant heat dissipation and data synchronization problems.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Various other methods are used to improve CPU performance.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Some instruction-level parallelism (ILP) methods such as superscalar pipelining are suitable for many applications, but are inefficient for others that contain difficult-to-predict code.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Many applications are better suited to thread-level parallelism (TLP) methods, and multiple independent CPUs are commonly used to increase a system's overall TLP.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] A combination of increased available space (due to refined manufacturing processes) and the demand for increased TLP led to the development of multi-core CPUs.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In 1985, Apple engineer Sam Holland convinced Apple to develop its own 4-processor CPU chip to power future Macs called Scorpius.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The processor's proposed feature set was highly ambitious, including four cores and SIMD (vector) support with inter-processor communication features.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] With the design beyond the fabrication capabilities of the time, the project was brought to an end in 1989.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the 1990s, Kunle Olukotun led the Stanford Hydra Chip Multiprocessor (CMP) research project.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This initiative was among the first to demonstrate the viability of integrating multiple processors on a single chip, a concept that laid the groundwork for today's multicore processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The Hydra project introduced support for thread-level speculation (TLS), enabling more efficient parallel execution of programs.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Several business motives drive the development of multi-core architectures.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] For decades, it was possible to improve performance of a CPU by shrinking the area of the integrated circuit (IC), which reduced the cost per device on the IC.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Alternatively, for the same circuit area, more transistors could be used in the design, which increased functionality, especially for complex instruction set computing (CISC) architectures.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Clock rates also increased by orders of magnitude in the decades of the late 20th century, from several megahertz in the 1980s to several gigahertz in the early 2000s.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] As the rate of clock speed improvements slowed, increased use of parallel computing in the form of multi-core processors has been pursued to improve overall processing performance.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Multiple cores were used on the same CPU chip, which could then lead to better sales of CPU chips with two or more cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] For example, Intel has produced a 48-core processor for research in cloud computing; each core has an x86 architecture.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Since computer manufacturers have long implemented symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) designs using discrete CPUs, the issues regarding implementing multi-core processor architecture and supporting it with software are well known.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The *ILP wall*; the increasing difficulty of finding enough parallelism in a single instruction stream to keep a high-performance single-core processor busy.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The *power wall*; the trend of consuming exponentially increasing power (and thus also generating exponentially increasing heat) with each factorial increase of operating frequency.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This increase can be mitigated by "shrinking" the processor by using smaller traces for the same logic.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The *power wall* poses manufacturing, system design and deployment problems that have not been justified in the face of the diminished gains in performance due to the *memory wall* and *ILP wall*.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In order to continue delivering regular performance improvements for general-purpose processors, manufacturers such as Intel and AMD have turned to multi-core designs, sacrificing lower manufacturing-costs for higher performance in some applications and systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Multi-core architectures are being developed, but so are the alternatives.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] An especially strong contender for established markets is the further integration of peripheral functions into the chip.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The proximity of multiple CPU cores on the same die allows the cache coherency circuitry to operate at a much higher clock rate than what is possible if the signals have to travel off-chip.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Combining equivalent CPUs on a single die significantly improves the performance of cache snoop (alternative: Bus snooping) operations.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Put simply, this means that signals between different CPUs travel shorter distances, and therefore those signals degrade less.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] These higher-quality signals allow more data to be sent in a given time period, since individual signals can be shorter and do not need to be repeated as often.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Assuming that the die can physically fit into the package, multi-core CPU designs require much less printed circuit board (PCB) space than do multi-chip SMP designs.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Also, a dual-core processor uses slightly less power than two coupled single-core processors, principally because of the decreased power required to drive signals external to the chip.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Furthermore, the cores share some circuitry, like the L2 cache and the interface to the front-side bus (FSB).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In terms of competing technologies for the available silicon die area, multi-core design can make use of proven CPU core library designs and produce a product with lower risk of design error than devising a new wider-core design.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Also, adding more cache suffers from diminishing returns.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Multi-core chips also allow higher performance at lower energy.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This can be a big factor in mobile devices that operate on batteries.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Since each core in a multi-core CPU is generally more energy-efficient, the chip becomes more efficient than having a single large monolithic core.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This allows higher performance with less energy.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] A challenge in this, however, is the additional overhead of writing parallel code.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Maximizing the usage of the computing resources provided by multi-core processors requires adjustments both to the operating system (OS) support and to existing application software.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Also, the ability of multi-core processors to increase application performance depends on the use of multiple threads within applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Integration of a multi-core chip can lower the chip production yields.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] They are also more difficult to manage thermally than lower-density single-core designs.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] From an architectural point of view, ultimately, single CPU designs may make better use of the silicon surface area than multiprocessing cores, so a development commitment to this architecture may carry the risk of obsolescence.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Finally, raw processing power is not the only constraint on system performance.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Two processing cores sharing the same system bus and memory bandwidth limits the real-world performance advantage.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The trend in processor development has been towards an ever-increasing number of cores, as processors with hundreds or even thousands of cores become theoretically possible.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In addition, multi-core chips mixed with simultaneous multithreading, memory-on-chip, and special-purpose "heterogeneous" (or asymmetric) cores promise further performance and efficiency gains, especially in processing multimedia, recognition and networking applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] For example, a big.LITTLE core includes a high-performance core (called 'big') and a low-power core (called 'LITTLE').
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] There is also a trend towards improving energy-efficiency by focusing on performance-per-watt with advanced fine-grain or ultra fine-grain power management and dynamic voltage and frequency scaling (i.e. laptop computers and portable media players).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Chips designed from the outset for a large number of cores (rather than having evolved from single core designs) are sometimes referred to as manycore designs, emphasising qualitative differences.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The composition and balance of the cores in multi-core architecture show great variety.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Some architectures use one core design repeated consistently ("homogeneous"), while others use a mixture of different cores, each optimized for a different, "heterogeneous" role.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] How multiple cores are implemented and integrated significantly affects both the developer's programming skills and the consumer's expectations of apps and interactivity versus the device.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] A device advertised as being octa-core will only have independent cores if advertised as *True Octa-core*, or similar styling, as opposed to being merely two sets of quad-cores each with fixed clock speeds.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] An outdated version of an anti-virus application may create a new thread for a scan process, while its GUI thread waits for commands from the user (e.g. cancel the scan).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In such cases, a multi-core architecture is of little benefit for the application itself due to the single thread doing all the heavy lifting and the inability to balance the work evenly across multiple cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Programming truly multithreaded code often requires complex co-ordination of threads and can easily introduce subtle and difficult-to-find bugs due to the interweaving of processing on data shared between threads (see thread-safety).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Consequently, such code is much more difficult to debug than single-threaded code when it breaks.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] There has been a perceived lack of motivation for writing consumer-level threaded applications because of the relative rarity of consumer-level demand for maximum use of computer hardware.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Also, serial tasks like decoding the entropy encoding algorithms used in video codecs are impossible to parallelize because each result generated is used to help create the next result of the entropy decoding algorithm.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] If developers are unable to design software to fully exploit the resources provided by multiple cores, then they will ultimately reach an insurmountable performance ceiling.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The telecommunications market had been one of the first that needed a new design of parallel datapath packet processing because there was a very quick adoption of these multiple-core processors for the datapath and the control plane.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] These MPUs are going to replace the traditional Network Processors that were based on proprietary microcode or picocode.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Parallel programming techniques can benefit from multiple cores directly.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Some existing parallel programming models such as Cilk Plus, OpenMP, OpenHMPP, FastFlow, Skandium, MPI, and Erlang can be used on multi-core platforms.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Intel introduced a new abstraction for C++ parallelism called TBB.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Other research efforts include the Codeplay Sieve System, Cray's Chapel, Sun's Fortress, and IBM's X10.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Multi-core processing has also affected the ability of modern computational software development.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Developers programming in newer languages might find that their modern languages do not support multi-core functionality.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This then requires the use of numerical libraries to access code written in languages like C and Fortran, which perform math computations faster than newer languages like C#.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Intel's MKL and AMD's ACML are written in these native languages and take advantage of multi-core processing.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Balancing the application workload across processors can be problematic, especially if they have different performance characteristics.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] There are different conceptual models to deal with the problem, for example using a coordination language and program building blocks (programming libraries or higher-order functions).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Each block can have a different native implementation for each processor type.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Users simply program using these abstractions and an intelligent compiler chooses the best implementation based on the context.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Managing concurrency acquires a central role in developing parallel applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The partitioning stage of a design is intended to expose opportunities for parallel execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Hence, the focus is on defining a large number of small tasks in order to yield what is termed a fine-grained decomposition of a problem.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The tasks generated by a partition are intended to execute concurrently but cannot, in general, execute independently.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The computation to be performed in one task will typically require data associated with another task.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Data must then be transferred between tasks so as to allow computation to proceed.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This information flow is specified in the communication phase of a design.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the third stage, development moves from the abstract toward the concrete.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Developers revisit decisions made in the partitioning and communication phases with a view to obtaining an algorithm that will execute efficiently on some class of parallel computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In particular, developers consider whether it is useful to combine, or agglomerate, tasks identified by the partitioning phase, so as to provide a smaller number of tasks, each of greater size.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] They also determine whether it is worthwhile to replicate data and computation.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In the fourth and final stage of the design of parallel algorithms, the developers specify where each task is to execute.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This mapping problem does not arise on uniprocessors or on shared-memory computers that provide automatic task scheduling.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] On the other hand, on the server side, multi-core processors are ideal because they allow many users to connect to a site simultaneously and have independent threads of execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This allows for Web servers and application servers that have much better throughput.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Vendors may license some software "per processor".
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] This can give rise to ambiguity, because a "processor" may consist either of a single core or of a combination of cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Embedded computing operates in an area of processor technology distinct from that of "mainstream" PCs.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The same technological drives towards multi-core apply here too.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Indeed, in many cases the application is a "natural" fit for multi-core technologies, if the task can easily be partitioned between the different processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In addition, embedded software is typically developed for a specific hardware release, making issues of software portability, legacy code or supporting independent developers less critical than is the case for PC or enterprise computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] As a result, it is easier for developers to adopt new technologies and as a result there is a greater variety of multi-core processing architectures and suppliers.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] As of 2010, multi-core network processors have become mainstream, with companies such as Freescale Semiconductor, Cavium Networks, Wintegra and Broadcom all manufacturing products with eight processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] For the system developer, a key challenge is how to exploit all the cores in these devices to achieve maximum networking performance at the system level, despite the performance limitations inherent in a symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) operating system.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Companies such as 6WIND provide portable packet processing software designed so that the networking data plane runs in a fast path environment outside the operating system of the network device.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In digital signal processing the same trend applies: Texas Instruments has the three-core TMS320C6488 and four-core TMS320C5441, Freescale the four-core MSC8144 and six-core MSC8156 (and both have stated they are working on eight-core successors).
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Newer entries include the Storm-1 family from Stream Processors, Inc with 40 and 80 general purpose ALUs per chip, all programmable in C as a SIMD engine and Picochip with 300 processors on a single die, focused on communication applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] In heterogeneous computing, where a system uses more than one kind of processor or cores, multi-core solutions are becoming more common: Xilinx Zynq UltraScale+ MPSoC has a quad-core ARM Cortex-A53 and dual-core ARM Cortex-R5.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Software solutions such as OpenAMP are being used to help with inter-processor communication.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Mobile devices may use the ARM big.LITTLE architecture.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] The research and development of multicore processors often compares many options, and benchmarks are developed to help such evaluations.
[src:rayon-parallel/multi-core-processor] Existing benchmarks include SPLASH-2, PARSEC, and COSMIC for heterogeneous systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:rayon-parallel/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:rayon-parallel/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In computer science, a **thread** of execution is the smallest sequence of programmed instructions that can be managed independently by a scheduler, which is typically a part of the operating system.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In many cases, a thread is a component of a process.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The multiple threads of a given process may be executed concurrently (via multithreading capabilities), sharing resources such as memory, while different processes do not share these resources.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In particular, the threads of a process share its executable code and the values of its dynamically allocated variables and non-thread-local global variables at any given time.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The implementation of threads and processes differs between operating systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Threads made an early appearance under the name of "tasks" in IBM's batch processing operating system, OS/360, in 1967.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] It provided users with three available configurations of the OS/360 control system, of which multiprogramming with a variable number of tasks (MVT) was one.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The Mach implementation of threads was described in the summer of 1986.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] OS/2 1.0, released in 1987, supported threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Digital Research's MP/M operating system provided multiprogramming, multi-tasking, and preemptive multi-tasking for the Intel 8080 processor in 1979, and on the 8086 processor in 1981.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The first version of Windows to have threads was Windows NT, which was released in 1993.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In 1995, the IEEE defined the pthreads API, which standardized an interface for portable multithreaded programming across a variety of Unix-like operating systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Since then, pthreads has also been implemented on Windows with third-party packages such as *pthreads-w32*, which implements the standard on top of the existing Windows API.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The use of threads in software applications became more common in the early 2000s as CPUs began to utilize multiple cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Applications wishing to take advantage of multiple cores for performance advantages were required to employ concurrency to utilize the multiple cores.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Scheduling can be done at the kernel level or user level, and multitasking can be done preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This yields a variety of related concepts.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] At the kernel level, a *process* contains one or more *kernel threads*, which share the process's resources, such as memory and file handles – a process is a unit of resources, while a thread is a unit of scheduling and execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Kernel scheduling is typically uniformly done preemptively or, less commonly, cooperatively.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] At the user level a process such as a runtime system can itself schedule multiple threads of execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] If these do not share data, as in Erlang, they are usually analogously called processes, while if they share data they are usually called *(user) threads*, particularly if preemptively scheduled.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Cooperatively scheduled user threads are known as *fibers*; different processes may schedule user threads differently.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] User threads may be executed by kernel threads in various ways (one-to-one, many-to-one, many-to-many).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The term *light-weight process* variously refers to user threads or to kernel mechanisms for scheduling user threads onto kernel threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A process is a heavyweight unit of kernel scheduling, as creating, destroying, and switching processes is relatively expensive.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Processes own resources allocated by the operating system.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Resources include memory (for both code and data), file handles, sockets, device handles, windows, and a process control block.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Processes are *isolated* by process isolation, and do not share address spaces or file resources except through explicit methods such as inheriting file handles or shared memory segments, or mapping the same file in a shared way – see Interprocess communication.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Creating or destroying a process is relatively expensive, as resources must be acquired or released.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A *kernel thread* is a lightweight unit of kernel scheduling.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] At least one kernel thread exists within each process.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] If multiple kernel threads exist within a process, then they share the same memory and file resources.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Kernel threads are preemptively multitasked if the operating system's process scheduler is preemptive.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Kernel threads do not own resources except for a stack, a copy of the registers including the program counter, and thread-local storage (if any), and are thus relatively cheap to create and destroy.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Thread switching is also relatively cheap: it requires a context switch (saving and restoring registers and stack pointer), but does not change virtual memory and is thus cache-friendly (leaving TLB valid).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The kernel can assign one or more software threads to each core in a CPU (it being able to assign itself multiple software threads depending on its support for multithreading), and can swap out threads that get blocked.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] However, kernel threads take much longer than user threads to be swapped.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Threads are sometimes implemented in userspace libraries, thus called *user threads*.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The kernel is unaware of them, so they are managed and scheduled in userspace.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Some implementations base their user threads on top of several kernel threads, to benefit from multi-processor machines (M:N model).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] User threads as implemented by virtual machines are also called green threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Since scheduling occurs in userspace, the scheduling policy can be more easily tailored to the requirements of the program's workload.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] However, the use of blocking system calls in user threads (as opposed to kernel threads) can be problematic.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] If a user thread or a fiber performs a system call that blocks, the other user threads and fibers in the process are unable to run until the system call returns.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A typical example of this problem is when performing I/O: most programs are written to perform I/O synchronously.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] When an I/O operation is initiated, a system call is made, and does not return until the I/O operation has been completed.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In the intervening period, the entire process is "blocked" by the kernel and cannot run, which starves other user threads and fibers in the same process from executing.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Similar solutions can be provided for other blocking system calls.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Alternatively, the program can be written to avoid the use of synchronous I/O or other blocking system calls (in particular, using non-blocking I/O, including lambda continuations and/or async/await primitives).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Fibers are an even lighter unit of scheduling which are cooperatively scheduled: a running fiber must explicitly *yield* to allow another fiber to run, which makes their implementation much easier than kernel or user threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A fiber can be scheduled to run in any thread in the same process.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This permits applications to gain performance improvements by managing scheduling themselves, instead of relying on the kernel scheduler (which may not be tuned for the application).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Some research implementations of the OpenMP parallel programming model implement their tasks through fibers.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Closely related to fibers are coroutines, with the distinction being that coroutines are a language-level construct, while fibers are a system-level construct.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Operating systems schedule threads either preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Multi-user operating systems generally favor preemptive multithreading for its finer-grained control over execution time via context switching.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] However, preemptive scheduling may context-switch threads at moments unanticipated by programmers, thus causing lock convoy, priority inversion, or other side-effects.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In contrast, cooperative multithreading relies on threads to relinquish control of execution, thus ensuring that threads run to completion.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This can cause problems if a cooperatively-multitasked thread blocks by waiting on a resource or if it starves other threads by not yielding control of execution during intensive computation.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Until the early 2000s, most desktop computers had only one single-core CPU, with no support for hardware threads, although threads were still used on such computers because switching between threads was generally still quicker than full-process context switches.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In 2002, Intel added support for simultaneous multithreading to the Pentium 4 processor, under the name *hyper-threading*; in 2005, they introduced the dual-core Pentium D processor and AMD introduced the dual-core Athlon 64 X2 processor.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Systems with a single processor generally implement multithreading by time slicing: the central processing unit (CPU) switches between different *software threads*.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This context switching usually occurs frequently enough that users perceive the threads or tasks as running in parallel (for popular server/desktop operating systems, maximum time slice of a thread, when other threads are waiting, is often limited to 100–200ms).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] On a multiprocessor or multi-core system, multiple threads can execute in parallel, with every processor or core executing a separate thread simultaneously; on a processor or core with *hardware threads*, separate software threads can also be executed concurrently by separate hardware threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Threads created by the user in a 1:1 correspondence with schedulable entities in the kernel are the simplest possible threading implementation.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] OS/2 and Win32 used this approach from the start, while on Linux the GNU C Library implements this approach (via the NPTL or older LinuxThreads).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This approach is also used by Solaris, NetBSD, FreeBSD, macOS, and iOS.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] An *M*:1 model implies that all application-level threads map to one kernel-level scheduled entity; the kernel has no knowledge of the application threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] With this approach, context switching can be done very quickly and, in addition, it can be implemented even on simple kernels which do not support threading.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] One of the major drawbacks, however, is that it cannot benefit from the hardware acceleration on multithreaded processors or multi-processor computers: there is never more than one thread being scheduled at the same time.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] For example: If one of the threads needs to execute an I/O request, the whole process is blocked and the threading advantage cannot be used.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The GNU Portable Threads uses User-level threading, as does State Threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] SunOS 4.x implemented *light-weight processes* or LWPs.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] NetBSD 2.x+, and DragonFly BSD implement LWPs as kernel threads (1:1 model).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] SunOS 5.2 through SunOS 5.8 as well as NetBSD 2 to NetBSD 4 implemented a two level model, multiplexing one or more user level threads on each kernel thread (M:N model).
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] SunOS 5.9 and later, as well as NetBSD 5 eliminated user threads support, returning to a 1:1 model.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] FreeBSD 6 supported both 1:1 and M:N, users could choose which one should be used with a given program using /etc/libmap.conf.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Starting with FreeBSD 7, the 1:1 became the default.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] FreeBSD 8 no longer supports the M:N model.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In computer programming, *single-threading* is the processing of one instruction at a time.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] In the formal analysis of the variables' semantics and process state, the term *single threading* can be used differently to mean "backtracking within a single thread", which is common in the functional programming community.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Multithreading is mainly found in multitasking operating systems.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Multithreading is a widespread programming and execution model that allows multiple threads to exist within the context of one process.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] These threads share the process's resources, but are able to execute independently.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The threaded programming model provides developers with a useful abstraction of concurrent execution.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Multithreading can also be applied to one process to enable parallel execution on a multiprocessing system.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Multithreading libraries tend to provide a function call to create a new thread, which takes a function as a parameter.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A concurrent thread is then created which starts running the passed function and ends when the function returns.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] The thread libraries also offer data synchronization functions.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Threads in the same process share the same address space.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This allows concurrently running code to couple tightly and conveniently exchange data without the overhead or complexity of an IPC.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] When shared between threads, however, even simple data structures become prone to race conditions if they require more than one CPU instruction to update: two threads may end up attempting to update the data structure at the same time and find it unexpectedly changing underfoot.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Bugs caused by race conditions can be very difficult to reproduce and isolate.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] To prevent this, threading application programming interfaces (APIs) offer synchronization primitives such as mutexes to lock data structures against concurrent access.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] On uniprocessor systems, a thread running into a locked mutex must sleep and hence trigger a context switch.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] On multi-processor systems, the thread may instead poll the mutex in a spinlock.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Both of these may sap performance and force processors in symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) systems to contend for the memory bus, especially if the granularity of the locking is too fine.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Other synchronization APIs include condition variables, critical sections, semaphores, and monitors.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] A popular programming pattern involving threads is that of thread pools where a set number of threads are created at startup that then wait for a task to be assigned.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] When a new task arrives, it wakes up, completes the task and goes back to waiting.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] This avoids the relatively expensive thread creation and destruction functions for every task performed and takes thread management out of the application developer's hand and leaves it to a library or the operating system that is better suited to optimize thread management.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] If all threads are busy, additional work items are placed in a queue until a thread becomes available to execute them.
[src:rayon-parallel/thread-computing] Many programming languages support threading in some capacity.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In parallel computing, **work stealing** is a scheduling strategy for multithreaded computer programs.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] It solves the problem of executing a *dynamically multithreaded* computation, one that can "spawn" new threads of execution, on a *statically multithreaded* computer, with a fixed number of processors (or cores).
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] It does so efficiently in terms of execution time, memory usage, and inter-processor communication.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In a work stealing scheduler, each processor in a computer system has a queue of work items (computational tasks, threads) to perform.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Each work item consists of a series of instructions, to be executed sequentially, but in the course of its execution, a work item may also *spawn* new work items that can feasibly be executed in parallel with its other work.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] These new items are initially put on the queue of the processor executing the work item.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] When a processor runs out of work, it looks at the queues of the other processors and "steals" their work items.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In effect, work stealing distributes the scheduling work over idle processors, and as long as all processors have work to do, no scheduling overhead occurs.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Work stealing contrasts with *work sharing*, another popular scheduling approach for dynamic multithreading, where each work item is scheduled onto a processor when it is spawned.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Compared to this approach, work stealing reduces the amount of process migration between processors, because no such migration occurs when all processors have work to do.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] The idea of work stealing goes back to the implementation of the Multilisp programming language and work on parallel functional programming languages in the 1980s.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] It is employed in the scheduler for the Cilk programming language, the Java fork/join framework, the .NET Task Parallel Library, and the Rust Tokio runtime.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Work stealing is designed for a "strict" fork–join model of parallel computation, which means that a computation can be viewed as a directed acyclic graph with a single source (start of computation) and a single sink (end of computation).
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Each node in this graph represents either a *fork* or a *join*.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Forks produce multiple *logically parallel* computations, variously called "threads" or "strands".
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In the graph, when two edges leave a node, the computations represented by the edge labels are logically parallel: they may be performed either in parallel, or sequentially.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] The computation may only proceed past a *join* node when the computations represented by its incoming edges are complete.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] The work of a scheduler, now, is to assign the computations (edges) to processors in a way that makes the entire computation run to completion in the correct order (as constrained by the join nodes), preferably as fast as possible.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] The randomized version of the work stealing algorithm presented by Blumofe and Leiserson maintains several threads of execution and schedules these onto P processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Each of the processors has a double-ended queue (deque) of threads.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Call the ends of the deque "top" and "bottom".
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Initially, a computation consists of a single thread and is assigned to some processor, while the other processors start off idle.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Note that, in the rule for *spawn*, Blumofe and Leiserson suggest that the "parent" thread execute its new thread, as if performing a function call (in the C-like program f(x); g(y);, the function call to f completes before the call to g is performed).
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] This is called "continuation stealing", because the continuation of the function can be stolen while the spawned thread is executed, and is the scheduling algorithm used in Cilk Plus.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] It is not the only way to implement work stealing; the alternative strategy is called "child stealing" and is easier to implement as a library, without compiler support.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Child stealing is used by Threading Building Blocks, Microsoft's Task Parallel Library and OpenMP, although the latter gives the programmer control over which strategy is used.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Several variants of work stealing have been proposed.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] This means that, in expectation, the time required is at most a constant factor times the theoretical minimum.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] However, the running time (in particular, the number of steals executed) can be exponential in $T_{\infty }$ in the worst case.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] A localized variant, in which a processor attempts to steal back its own work whenever it is free, has also been analyzed theoretically and practically.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] A computation scheduled by the Blumofe–Leiserson version of work stealing uses $O(S_{1}P)$ stack space, if $S_{1}$ were the stack usage of the same computation on a single processor, fitting the authors' own earlier definition of space efficiency.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In a child-stealing implementation, all "forked" calls to f are put in a work queue that thus grows to size n, which can be made arbitrarily large.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] The work stealing algorithm as outlined earlier, and its analysis, assume a computing environment where a computation is scheduled onto a set of dedicated processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In a multiprogramming (multi-tasking) environment, the algorithm must be modified to instead schedule computation tasks onto a pool of worker threads, which in turn are scheduled onto the actual processors by an operating system scheduler.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] At any given time, the OS scheduler will assign to the work stealing process some number *PA* ≤ *P* of the P processors in the computer, because other processes may be using the remaining processors.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] In this setting, work stealing with a pool of P worker threads has the problem that workers acting as thieves may cause livelock: they may block the execution of workers that would actually spawn useful tasks.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] where *P*avg is the average number of processors allocated to the computation by the OS scheduler over the computation's running time.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Attempts to improve on the multiprogramming work stealer have focused on cache locality issues and improved queue data structures.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Several scheduling algorithms for dynamically multithreaded computations compete with work stealing.
[src:rayon-parallel/work-stealing] Besides the traditional work sharing approach, there is a scheduler called *parallel depth-first* (PDF) that improves on the space bounds of work stealing, as well giving better performance in some situations where the cores of a chip multiprocessor share a cache.
